and at the beginning of the 12th century by the Norman baron William de Graham, holder of the manor of Grantham in Lincolnshire, from whom many if not all modern bearers are probably descended. The chief of Clan Graham is the Duke of Montrose."],"variants":[{"name":"Greim","meanings":["South German: from a short form of a compound personal name beginning with the element <i>grīm</i> ‘mask, helmet’.","Scottish: variant of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahm","meanings":["(1997: 107;2007: 460; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire and northern England): shortened form of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grantham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, of uncertain origin. The final element is Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’; the first may be Old English <i>grand</i> ‘gravel’ or perhaps a personal name <i>Granta</i>, which probably originated as a byname meaning ‘snarler’. See also   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahame","meanings":["(1997: 113;2007: 164; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Graham  . — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is as high as 261, while the figure for 2010 is supposedly lower than 100."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert Graham was born in 1281, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Robert Graham. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1281–":"1281–Surnud","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1317–Female":"1317–Surnud","1281–Female":"1281–Surnud","about 1317":"umbes 1317","1275":"1275","1281":"1281","1317":"1317","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1281–":"1281–Kuollut","1275–Male":"1275–Kuollut","1317–Female":"1317–Kuollut","1281–Female":"1281–Kuollut","about 1317":"noin 1317","1275":"1275","1281":"1281","1317":"1317","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"1281–":"1281–Décédée","1275–Male":"1275–Décédé","1317–Female":"1317–Décédée","1281–Female":"1281–Décédée","about 1317":"environ 1317","1275":"1275","1281":"1281","1317":"1317","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Devon, England":"Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert Graham est née en 1281, à Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Robert Graham. Elle est décédée dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1281–":"1281–Verstorben","1275–Male":"1275–Verstorben","1317–Female":"1317–Verstorben","1281–Female":"1281–Verstorben","about 1317":"um 1317","1275":"1275","1281":"1281","1317":"1317","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert Graham wurde 1281 in Devon, England, United Kingdom geboren. Sie hatte mit Robert Graham mindestens 1 Tochter. Sie starb in ihrem Geburtsort."},"ht":{"1281–":"1281–Desede","1275–Male":"1275–Desede","1317–Female":"1317–Desede","1281–Female":"1281–Des